            <p>+ <choice>
                  <sic>Ἷς</sic>
                  <corr>Εἷς</corr>
               </choice> Θεός, ὁ πἀντων Δεσ<lb/>πότης. <choice>
                  <sic>Μνημεῖαν</sic>
                  <corr>Μνημεῖον</corr>
               </choice> Κύρας<lb/> Κασσισέου, ἀποθανοῦσ<unclear>α</unclear>
               <lb/>
                    μετὰ καλοῦ <choice>
                  <sic>ἀνῶματος</sic>
                  <corr>ὀνόματος</corr>
               </choice>
               <lb/> καὶ κ<unclear>αλῆς</unclear>
                    πίστεως ἐτῶ<lb/>
               <supplied reason="undefined">ν</supplied>
               <gap reason="illegible"><?human @extent=ca. 17-18 @unit=characters ?></gap>
               <lb/>
               <gap reason="illegible"><?human @extent=ca. 12-13 @unit=characters ?></gap>
               <supplied reason="undefined">
                  <unclear>Ξ</unclear>ανθι</supplied>
               <lb/>κοῦ δευτέρᾳ <choice>
                  <abbr>ἠμ</abbr>
                  <expan>ἡμέρᾳ</expan>
               </choice> Κυρίου <lb/>
               <gap reason="illegible"/>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0312.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0312.transcription">
            <p> One (is) the God, the Lord of all. Monument of Kyra (daughter) of Kassisseos,
                    who died having a good name and good faith (at the age) of...on the second (day)
                    of [the month Xan]thikos, on the ...day of the...Lord..</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription provides a day and a month, the 2nd of Xanthikos (March 23), but not a year. Still, the inscription has been dated on the strength of other factors to the second half of the fifth century CE. The tombstone is rectangular, with damage around its corners. Lines 1 through 5 and line 8 are engraved, while 1 and 4 preserve red paint. Lines 6, 7, and 9 are attested by traces of red paint, though they are almost entirely lost. A cross is engraved at the beginning of the first line of text. The author notes that the names which appear in this inscription are also found elsewhere at Ghor es-Safi.</p>
         </div>
